The Martin Kleppmann style first-principles explanation of the diff has been authored and published as a comment on Pull Request [#38](https://github.com/kovartravis/splash/pull/38#issuecomment-5033420828).

### Posted PR Explanation Summary

> When building a terminal multiplexer and agent harness like Splash, one of the central architectural challenges is managing shared environment state across process boundaries. Splash runs an embedded Model Context Protocol (MCP) server on a dynamic local port to let external AI coding harnesses—such as `agy`—communicate back with Splash. However, out-of-the-box CLI agents rely on configuration files on disk (like `mcp_config.json`) to discover available MCP server endpoints. If a tool writes to a configuration file while running but leaves that file unchanged upon exit, subsequent independent invocations of the CLI tool will attempt to connect to an offline port, causing silent connection timeouts or degraded behavior.
>
> To solve this cleanly, we introduced an explicit ownership model for external configuration files centered around the Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII) pattern in Rust. The new `McpConfigGuard` struct encapsulates both the lifetime of an MCP server registration entry and the disk state of the configuration file itself. When an `agy` harness tab is spawned, `McpConfigGuard::register` reads the target `mcp_config.json` path, records whether the file already existed or was created fresh by Splash, and safely inserts the `"splash"` server entry under the `"mcpServers"` object key.
>
> A critical design constraint of configuration file management is preserving user state. Users often have pre-existing custom MCP servers configured in `mcp_config.json` prior to launching Splash. Rather than overwriting the entire file, `McpConfigGuard` performs selective JSON object mutation: it parses existing JSON content into an in-memory tree, appends or updates only the `"splash"` key entry, and writes back the pretty-printed JSON. This guarantees that pre-existing server declarations remain completely intact throughout Splash's execution.
>
> The true power of this RAII design emerges during cleanup. By implementing Rust's `Drop` trait on `McpConfigGuard`, cleanup is guaranteed by the compiler whenever the guard instance falls out of scope—whether because the user closes the active harness tab, the application shuts down, or an error occurs. When dropped, if the configuration file was originally created by Splash, the guard deletes the file entirely from disk. If the file pre-existed, the guard surgically removes only the `"splash"` key from `"mcpServers"` while serializing the remaining user configuration safely back to disk.
>
> At the system level, `McpConfigGuard` is integrated directly into Splash's `HarnessTab` struct inside `src/app.rs`. When `spawn_pty()` is called for an `agy` command, Splash registers the `McpConfigGuard` *before* spawning the child process. This ensures that the `"splash"` server registration is already flushed to disk before `agy` executes its initial startup sequence. We verified this entire lifecycle with both unit tests and an end-to-end integration test (`tests/agy_mcp_config_integration.rs`) that simulates real user keybindings—opening a launcher, spawning `agy`, inspecting disk state, and closing the tab—confirming deterministic cleanup across the full process lifecycle.
